  title="Tack — AI Agent Intent Language"
  description="Compressed intent language. The OS learns your vocabulary over time. Communication gets shorter as you work."
  relatedPages={relatedPages}
>
  <h2>What tack is</h2>
  <p>
    Tack is the operator intent language in the TUI. You type intent into the tack bar. The kernel resolves it — sometimes to a command, sometimes to an LLM query, sometimes to a needle reference.
  </p>

  <h2>Grammar</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong><code>:</code> prefix</strong> — Hard command. Dispatches directly to the kernel. <code>:compile</code>, <code>:reap</code>, <code>:status</code>.</li>
    <li><strong><code>.?</code> prefix</strong> — Soft probe. Queries the OS through the LLM. <code>.? what is store</code>.</li>
    <li><strong><code>→NNN</code></strong> — Needle reference. <code>→573</code> opens that needle.</li>
    <li><strong>Bare text</strong> — Filed as hay (raw unstructured intent). Later compiled into needles via <code>:compile</code>.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>The .language file</h2>
  <p>
    The OS maintains a <code>.language</code> file — a pipe-delimited table of verbs, their tiers, layers, and usage momentum. As you use verbs, their momentum increases. Unused verbs decay. The kernel loads high-momentum verbs at boot and demand-spawns the rest.
  </p>
  <p>
    Over time, your tack vocabulary converges on the commands you actually use. The OS adapts to you, not the other way around.
  </p>
</FeaturePage>
